<gtr:projectOverview xmlns:gtr="http://gtr.ukri.org/api"><gtr:projectComposition><gtr:collaborations/><gtr:leadResearchOrganisation url="http://gtr.ukri.org:80/organisation/3EAE04CA-9D62-4483-B9C4-F91AD9F4C5A9"><gtr:id>3EAE04CA-9D62-4483-B9C4-F91AD9F4C5A9</gtr:id><gtr:name>University of Oxford</gtr:name><gtr:department>Sir William Dunn Sch of Pathology</gtr:department><gtr:address><gtr:line1>University Chest</gtr:line1><gtr:line2>Wellington Square</gtr:line2><gtr:line4>Oxford</gtr:line4><gtr:postCode>OX1 2JD</gtr:postCode><gtr:region>South East</gtr:region><gtr:country>United Kingdom</gtr:country></gtr:address><gtr:typeInd>RO</gtr:typeInd></gtr:leadResearchOrganisation><gtr:organisationRoles><gtr:organisationRole url="http://gtr.ukri.org:80/organisation/3EAE04CA-9D62-4483-B9C4-F91AD9F4C5A9"><gtr:id>3EAE04CA-9D62-4483-B9C4-F91AD9F4C5A9</gtr:id><gtr:name>University of Oxford</gtr:name><gtr:address><gtr:line1>University Chest</gtr:line1><gtr:line2>Wellington Square</gtr:line2><gtr:line4>Oxford</gtr:line4><gtr:postCode>OX1 2JD</gtr:postCode><gtr:region>South East</gtr:region><gtr:country>United Kingdom</gtr:country></gtr:address><gtr:roles><gtr:role><gtr:name>LEAD_RO</gtr:name></gtr:role></gtr:roles></gtr:organisationRole></gtr:organisationRoles><gtr:personRoles><gtr:personRole url="http://gtr.ukri.org:80/person/A0E8F695-9B5C-45A6-A2CA-4EDD880E9D53"><gtr:id>A0E8F695-9B5C-45A6-A2CA-4EDD880E9D53</gtr:id><gtr:firstName>Thomas</gtr:firstName><gtr:surname>Harder</gtr:surname><gtr:roles><gtr:role><gtr:name>PRINCIPAL_INVESTIGATOR</gtr:name></gtr:role></gtr:roles></gtr:personRole></gtr:personRoles><gtr:project url="http://gtr.ukri.org:80/projects?ref=BB%2FC503803%2F1"><gtr:id>4D95170E-8C82-48C4-8853-630B0C5AE2A2</gtr:id><gtr:title>Cooperativity of grb2 binding plasma membrane linker LAT: Modelling the formation of signalling networks in membrane domains</gtr:title><gtr:status>Closed</gtr:status><gtr:grantCategory>Research Grant</gtr:grantCategory><gtr:grantReference>BB/C503803/1</gtr:grantReference><gtr:abstractText>Abstracts are not currently available in GtR for all funded research. This is normally because the abstract was not required at the time of proposal submission, but may be because it included sensitive information such as personal details.</gtr:abstractText><gtr:technicalSummary>Engagement of the T cell antigen receptor initiates a signalling cascade that results in T cell proliferation, cytokine production, and effector responses. The formation of multimolecular signalling complexes in plasma membrane domains is critical for connecting the TCR to intracellular signalling reactions. Linker for activation T cells (LAT), a palmitoylated transmembrane molecule, is the central nucleator of these signalling assemblies. LAT contains phosphotyrosine-based binding sites (PYBs) for SH2 domain-containing signalling proteins. Our previous work showed that the LAT&amp;iquest;s PYBs cooperate in the assembly of LAT and cytoplasmic signalling proteins into signalling complexes. The molecular basis for this cooperativity is not known. It may involve formation of lateral assemblies of LAT crosslinked by adaptor proteins or may be driven by cooperative binding of multiple proteins to a single LAT molecule. We will elucidate the molecular principles driving the formation of cooperative LAT signalling assemblies focusing on recruitment of grb2 to LAT&amp;iquest;s synergistic grb2-binding PYBs 7, 8, 9. We will employ Biacore Plasmon resonance to measure the binding of recombinant grb2 to LAT. LAT will be stably expressed in SL3 Drosophila cells as a Lck-chimera anchored in the inner leaflet of the plasma membrane by myristoylation and palmitoylation. Our preliminary characterisation showed that phosphorylation of PYBs in myr/palm LAT is efficiently induced by pervanadate-treatment of the SL3 cells. Phosphorylated LAT is purified from octylglucoside-solubilised membranes via His tag/Ni NTA affinity chromatography. We will generate LAT versions containing single grb2 PYBs 7, 8 or 9; all distal PYBs 789; and PYB combinations 78, 89 and 79. Moreover, binding affinity of grb2 to immobilised phosphotyrosyl peptides covering single LAT PYBs will be determined. The recombinant LAT will contain a consensus peptide for in vitro biotinylation between the membrane anchor and the LAT cytoplasc domain. In order to monitor cooperativity of grb2 recruitment on a single molecule, LAT variants will be immobilised on Biacore sensor chips via avidin. In order to measure grb2 incorporation to LAT assemblies, LAT will also be incorporated into lipid monolayers on hydrophobic sensor chips via their fatty acylations allowing lateral mobility of the LAT variants. Moreover, we will image LAT grb2 assemblies using lipid monolayers on glass coverslips. Myr/palm LAT variants will be incorporated into these monolayers and binding of recombinant grb2 labelled with commercial fluorescent dyes will be monitored by fluorescence microscopy. In summary this proposal has pioneering character, as it aims at understanding the as yet unstudied formation of signalling assemblies at the plasma membrane.</gtr:technicalSummary><gtr:fund><gtr:end>2009-06-14</gtr:end><gtr:funder url="http://gtr.ukri.org:80/organisation/2512EF1C-401B-4222-9869-A770D4C5FAC7"><gtr:id>2512EF1C-401B-4222-9869-A770D4C5FAC7</gtr:id><gtr:name>BBSRC</gtr:name></gtr:funder><gtr:start>2006-04-15</gtr:start><gtr:type>INCOME_ACTUAL</gtr:type><gtr:valuePounds>175361</gtr:valuePounds></gtr:fund><gtr:output><gtr:artisticAndCreativeProductOutputs/><gtr:collaborationOutputs/><gtr:disseminationOutputs/><gtr:exploitationOutputs/><gtr:furtherFundingOutputs/><gtr:impactSummaryOutputs/><gtr:intellectualPropertyOutputs/><gtr:otherResearchOutputs/><gtr:policyInfluenceOutputs/><gtr:productOutputs/><gtr:researchDatabaseAndModelOutputs/><gtr:researchMaterialOutputs/><gtr:softwareAndTechnicalProductOutputs/><gtr:spinOutOutputs/></gtr:output><gtr:publications><gtr:publication><gtr:id>E84F1C48-6E56-4191-B58C-3899CCF61F21</gtr:id><gtr:title>Phosphotyrosine-dependent in vitro reconstitution of recombinant LAT-nucleated multiprotein signalling complexes on liposomes.</gtr:title><gtr:parentPublicationTitle>Molecular membrane biology</gtr:parentPublicationTitle><gtr:authors><gtr:author url="http://gtr.ukri.org:80/person/8987ad0542f1e49d483c49311c660196"><gtr:id>8987ad0542f1e49d483c49311c660196</gtr:id><gtr:otherNames>Sangani D</gtr:otherNames></gtr:author></gtr:authors><gtr:date>2009-01-01</gtr:date><gtr:issn>0968-7688</gtr:issn><gtr:outcomeId>56758b6be679a</gtr:outcomeId></gtr:publication></gtr:publications><gtr:identifiers><gtr:identifier type="RCUK">BB/C503803/1</gtr:identifier></gtr:identifiers><gtr:healthCategories/><gtr:researchActivities/><gtr:researchSubjects/><gtr:researchTopics><gtr:researchTopic><gtr:id>D05BC2E0-0345-4A3F-8C3F-775BC42A0819</gtr:id><gtr:text>Unclassified</gtr:text></gtr:researchTopic></gtr:researchTopics><gtr:rcukProgrammes/></gtr:project></gtr:projectComposition></gtr:projectOverview>